---
import GetStartedLayout from "../../layouts/GetStartedLayout.astro";
---

<GetStartedLayout
  title="Design principles"
  current="principles"
  description="How Prism resolves trade-offs: clarity, systems, accessibility, and resilient layouts."
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <h1 data-i18n="getStarted.principles.h2">Design principles</h1>
    <p class="intro" data-i18n="getStarted.principles.intro">
      When two patterns both seem reasonable, principles describe what we protect first.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="block">
    <ol class="principles">
      <li>
        <h3 data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.clarity.title">Clarity over cleverness</h3>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.clarity.body">
          Interfaces should explain themselves. Favor obvious paths, predictable controls, and copy that
          states outcomes in plain language—especially for errors, permissions, and empty states.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3 data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.systems.title">Systems, not souvenirs</h3>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.systems.body">
          If a pattern will ship more than once, it belongs in the system. Local experiments are welcome;
          successful ones graduate into tokens and components so everyone benefits.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3 data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.accessible.title">Accessibility is a product feature</h3>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.accessible.body">
          Contrast, keyboard flows, focus order, and assistive labels are part of the user story—not a
          late audit. We design and build for real settings: bright rooms, small screens, and motor
          variance.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3 data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.calm.title">Calm craft under pressure</h3>
        <p data-i18n="getStarted.principles.items.calm.body">
          Density should flex without breaking rhythm. Long labels, partial data, and narrow viewports are
          normal conditions, not edge cases—layouts and components need to hold up gracefully.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <p class="next">
    <a class="next-link" href="/get-started/language" data-i18n="getStarted.nextLanguage">Design language</a>
  </p>
</GetStartedLayout>
